# DOCS

## Introduction

This is the storth programming language docs. This file will contain all the information you need of
how to use and program in storth programming language.To begin with it is an AOT time compiler.
It uses its own backend(except assembler) with SSA IR. Do note that for now it only supports linux x86_64 machine.

## Syntax
The simplest program you can have is an empty main function. This main function will contain just the return.
Semi colons are mandatory.
`src_code
fn main() -> i32 {
    return 0;
}
`
To compile it you would just call `storthc filename.st`.
Refer to the help of the compiler by running storthc --help to see what you can do.
Basic syntax is driven by expressions. To define variable you would use go style syntax.

`src_code
x := 20; // This is defining a variable x of type i64.
`
To do type change in declaration you would specify the type after the colon.
`src_code
x : u32 = 20; // This is defining a variable x of type u32.
`

Refer to the types section to see all the available primitive types and how they work and also inspect their sizes.

### Structs

Structs are also defined the using the same concept.
`src_code
struct Foo {
    name: string;
    age: u32;
}
`

To create an instance of that strcture you would do:
`src_code
f := Foo{}; // This will initalize all the members to be 0.
f := Foo{"Urmom", 20}; // This is deseganted initalizer from C.
f := Foo{age = 20, name = "Aboba"}; // This is named initialization 
`
Type declaration will also memset the members to 0 meaning puttin `{}` is optional;

`src_code
f : Foo; // This is the same as f := Foo{};
`
Refer the type section to see all of the alignment and memory layout of structures.

### Tag Union
Tag union and structs have the same declaration but fundamentally operate differently.

`src_code
tag_union Foo {
    name: string;
    age: u32;
}
`

In tag unions the concept comes from rust where we have an intrinsic tag(refer to intrinsics) 
that will store the id of the active member to make it so that inactive member is inaccessible.

`src_code
f : tag_union;
f.tag = Foo.age;  // This will make name inaccessible member
f.name = "Urmom"; // This is an invalid code because you are trying to access an inactive tag name
                  // while age is the acctive one meaning only f.age is accessible.
`

### Enums and Enum_Flags
Enums work the exact same way enums from C work. They are completely identical.
The `: u32` is optional it means we can have optional specifier of types of enum by default it will be i64 but it is customizable.

`src_code
enum Foo : u32 {
    Name;
    Age;
}

f := Name;
`

Enum flags are one time set unchangable option we use so we can have enums are return code without modifying their value
`src_code
enum_flag Foo : u32 {
    Name := 30;
    Age := 40; // Invalid it must be kept in order so that later down the line we do not add a
               // member and modify the pre existing value.
}

f := Foo.Name;
`


### Functions

This is the simplest function we can write. The arrow will denote the return type.

`src_code
fn add(x: i32, y: u32) -> i64 {
    return x #as i64 + y #as i64;
}
`

We can have multiple returns from a function.

`src_code
fn foo() -> (string, u32) {
    return "Foo", 60;
}
`

A function modifies it state. We can accept values via pointer to modify the existing state of a variable.

`src_code
struct Foo {
    name: string;
    age: u32;
}

fn foo(f: *Foo) -> void {
    f.name = "Urmom";
    f.age = 20 #as u32;
}

fn main() -> i32 {
    f : Foo;
    foo(&f);
}
`
This is the simplest way we can modify struct values do note that the `.` operator does auto dereferencing.
Fundamentally functions are the same thing you would expect them to be however there is a notion of scoped function.
How many times have you done this in C you want a function declare it as static so it can be reused in a function.
That does not prevent it or is nicely usable to the level of defning the function inside.
So storth have the freedom of defining functions with in functions.
`src_code
fn foo() -> void {
   fn bar() -> i32 {
      return 69;
   }

   x := bar();
   y := bar();
}
`
This function bar is completely inacessible by functions of the outside world making it truely local to that specific defintion.
Functions can also have default parameters. These default params can be named parameters to be modfied.
The idea of positionally named argument is that the compiler already knows what variable is associated with
which argument so hard locking on the argument position is stupid for that regard.

`src_code
fn foo(name := "String", age : u32 = 32) -> void {
   print("%", name);
}

fn main() -> i32 {
   foo();
   foo("Aboba");
   foo(age = 40 #as u32, name = "Testing");
   return 0;
}
`
Functions are just reusable code that means for functions we do not understand the type it is important for us to have
generalization and for that we infact do have templates. Refer to the temnplate section to see what they are.

## Operators
We talked about functions now lets discuss the type of operatator you have. The operators and their presidence is coming from
C where all the operators have their own symbol and meaning.

### Single sign operations

Operator + : is used for addition.
Operator - : is used for subtraction.
Operator / : is used for division.
Operator * : is used for multiplication. If called from type specifier then it will become a pointer to that memory.
Operator & : is used for reference. So that we can do x := 20 then have p := &x.


### Double sign operations

Operator == : is used for comparision and checks if the comprands are equal.
Operator != : is used for comparision and checks if the comprands are not equal.
Operator ++ : is used for for incrementation and only post incrementation is valid preincrement is invalid.
Operator -- : is used for for decrementation and only post decrementation is valid predecrement is invalid.
Operator += : is used for for decrementation and only post decrementation is valid predecrement is invalid.
Operator -= : is used for for decrementation and only post decrementation is valid predecrement is invalid.
Operator *= : is used for for decrementation and only post decrementation is valid predecrement is invalid.
Operator /= : is used for for decrementation and only post decrementation is valid predecrement is invalid.
